msgid ""
"let\n"
" x = 1;\n"
" y = 2;\n"
"in x + y"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:231
msgid "let x=1;y=2;in x+y"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:242
msgid "Names and values"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:244
msgid ""
"Values in the Nix language can be primitive data types, lists, attribute "
"sets, and functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:246
msgid ""
"We show examples of primitive data types and lists in the context of "
"[attribute sets](attrset). Later in this section we cover special features "
"of character strings: [string interpolation](string-interpolation), [file "
"system paths](file-system-paths), and [indented strings](indented-strings). "
"We deal with [functions](functions) separately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:250
msgid ""
"[Attribute sets](attrset) and [`let` expressions](let) are used to assign "
"names to values. Assignments are denoted by a single equal sign (`=`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:253
msgid "Whenever you encounter an equal sign (`=`) in Nix language code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:254
msgid "On its left is the assigned name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:255
msgid "On its right is the value, delimited by a semicolon (`;`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:258
msgid "Attribute set `{ ... }`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:260
msgid ""
"An attribute set is a collection of name-value-pairs, where names must be "
"unique."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:262
msgid ""
"The following example shows all primitive data types, lists, and attribute "
"sets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:265
msgid ""
"If you are familiar with JSON, imagine the Nix language as *JSON with "
"functions*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:267
msgid ""
"Nix language data types *without functions* work just like their "
"counterparts in JSON and look very similar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:275
msgid "**Nix**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:276
msgid ""
"{\n"
"  string = \"hello\";\n"
"  integer = 1;\n"
"  float = 3.141;\n"
"  bool = true;\n"
"  null = null;\n"
"  list = [ 1 \"two\" false ];\n"
"  attribute-set = {\n"
"    a = \"hello\";\n"
"    b = 2;\n"
"    c = 2.718;\n"
"    d = false;\n"
"  }; # comments are supported\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:294
msgid "**JSON**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:295
msgid ""
"{\n"
"  \"string\": \"hello\",\n"
"  \"integer\": 1,\n"
"  \"float\": 3.141,\n"
"  \"bool\": true,\n"
"  \"null\": null,\n"
"  \"list\": [1, \"two\", false],\n"
"  \"object\": {\n"
"    \"a\": \"hello\",\n"
"    \"b\": 1,\n"
"    \"c\": 2.718,\n"
"    \"d\": false\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:314
msgid "Attribute names usually do not need quotes.[^attrnames]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:315
msgid "List elements are separated by white space.[^list-whitespace]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:322
msgid "Recursive attribute set `rec { ... }`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:324
msgid ""
"You will sometimes see attribute sets declared with `rec` prepended. This "
"allows access to attributes from within the set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:329
msgid ""
"rec {\n"
"  one = 1;\n"
"  two = one + 1;\n"
"  three = two + 1;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:338
msgid "{ one = 1; three = 3; two = 2; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:344
msgid ""
"Elements in an attribute set can be declared in any order, and are ordered "
"on evaluation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:347
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:520
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:632
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:785
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1368
msgid "Counter-example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:349
msgid ""
"{\n"
"  one = 1;\n"
"  two = one + 1;\n"
"  three = two + 1;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:358
msgid ""
"error: undefined variable 'one'\n"
"\n"
"       at «string»:3:9:\n"
"\n"
"            2|   one = 1;\n"
"            3|   two = one + 1;\n"
"             |         ^\n"
"            4|   three = two + 1;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:371
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:461
msgid "`let ... in ...`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:373
msgid "Also known as “`let` expression” or “`let` binding”"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:375
msgid "`let` expressions allow assigning names to values for repeated use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:379
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  a = 1;\n"
"in\n"
"a + a"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:387
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1165
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1213
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1607
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1628
msgid "2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:394
msgid ""
"Assignments are placed between the keywords `let` and `in`. In this example "
"we assign `a = 1`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:397
msgid ""
"After `in` comes the expression in which the assignments are valid, i.e., "
"where assigned names can be used. In this example the expression is `a + a`, "
"where `a` refers to `a = 1`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:400
msgid ""
"By replacing the names with their assigned values, `a + a` evaluates to `2`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:404
msgid ""
"Names can be assigned in any order, and expressions on the right of the "
"assignment (`=`) can refer to other assigned names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:408
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  b = a + 1;\n"
"  a = 1;\n"
"in\n"
"a + b"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:424
msgid ""
"Assignments are placed between the keywords `let` and `in`. In this example "
"we assign `a = 1` and `b = a + 1`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:427
msgid ""
"The order of assignments does not matter. Therefore the following example, "
"where the assignments are in reverse order, is equivalent:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:431
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  a = 1;\n"
"  b = a + 1;\n"
"in\n"
"a + b"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:445
msgid "Note that the `a` in `b = a + 1` refers to `a = 1`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:447
msgid ""
"After `in` comes the expression in which the assignments are valid. In this "
"example the expression is `a + b`, where `a` refers to `a = 1`, and `b` "
"refers to `b = a + 1`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:450
msgid ""
"By replacing the names with their assigned values, `a + b` evaluates to `3`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:452
msgid ""
"This is similar to [recursive attribute sets](rec-attrset): in both, the "
"order of assignments does not matter, and names on the left can be used in "
"expressions on the right of the assignment (`=`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:463
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  b = a + 1;\n"
"  c = a + b;\n"
"  a = 1;\n"
"in {  c = c; a = a; b = b; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:472
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:490
msgid "{ a = 1; b = 2; c = 3; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:479
msgid "`rec { ... }`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:481
msgid ""
"rec {\n"
"  b = a + 1;\n"
"  c = a + b;\n"
"  a = 1;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:497
msgid ""
"The difference is that while a recursive attribute set evaluates to an "
"[attribute set](attrset), any expression can follow after the `in` keyword."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:499
msgid "In the following example we use the `let` expression to form a list:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:501
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  b = a + 1;\n"
"  c = a + b;\n"
"  a = 1;\n"
"in [ a b c ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:510
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:613
msgid "[ 1 2 3 ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:517
msgid ""
"Only expressions within the `let` expression itself can access the newly "
"declared names. We say: the bindings have local scope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:522
msgid ""
"{\n"
"  a = let x = 1; in x;\n"
"  b = x;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:530
msgid ""
"error: undefined variable 'x'\n"
"\n"
"       at «string»:3:7:\n"
"\n"
"            2|   a = let x = 1; in x;\n"
"            3|   b = x;\n"
"             |       ^\n"
"            4| }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:542
msgid ""
"<!-- TODO: exercise - use let to reuse a value in an attribute set -->\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:544
msgid "Attribute access"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:546
msgid ""
"Attributes in a set are accessed with a dot (`.`) and the attribute name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:550
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  attrset = { x = 1; };\n"
"in\n"
"attrset.x"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:558
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:575
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1180
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1199
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1412
msgid "1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:563
msgid "Accessing nested attributes works the same way."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:567
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  attrset = { a = { b = { c = 1; }; }; };\n"
"in\n"
"attrset.a.b.c"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:580
msgid "The dot (`.`) notation can also be used for assigning attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:584
msgid "{ a.b.c = 1; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:589
msgid "{ a = { b = { c = 1; }; }; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:595
msgid "`with ...; ...`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:597
msgid ""
"The `with` expression allows access to attributes without repeatedly "
"referencing their attribute set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:601
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  a = {\n"
"    x = 1;\n"
"    y = 2;\n"
"    z = 3;\n"
"  };\n"
"in\n"
"with a; [ x y z ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:618
msgid "The expression"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:620
msgid "with a; [ x y z ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:624
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:690
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:721
msgid "is equivalent to"
msgstr "等價於"

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:626
msgid "[ a.x a.y a.z ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:630
msgid ""
"Attributes made available through `with` are only in scope of the expression "
"following the semicolon (`;`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:634
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  a = {\n"
"    x = 1;\n"
"    y = 2;\n"
"    z = 3;\n"
"  };\n"
"in\n"
"{\n"
"  b = with a; [ x y z ];\n"
"  c = x;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:649
msgid ""
"error: undefined variable 'x'\n"
"\n"
"       at «string»:10:7:\n"
"\n"
"            9|   b = with a; [ x y z ];\n"
"           10|   c = x;\n"
"             |       ^\n"
"           11| }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:662
msgid "`inherit ...`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:664
msgid ""
"`inherit` is shorthand for assigning the value of a name from an existing "
"scope to the same name in a nested scope. It is for convenience to avoid "
"repeating the same name multiple times."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:669
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  x = 1;\n"
"  y = 2;\n"
"in\n"
"{\n"
"  inherit x y;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:680
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:710
msgid "{ x = 1; y = 2; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:685
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:715
msgid "The fragment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:687
msgid "inherit x y;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:692
msgid "x = x; y = y;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:696
msgid ""
"It is also possible to `inherit` names from a specific attribute set with "
"parentheses (`inherit (...) ...`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:700
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  a = { x = 1; y = 2; };\n"
"in\n"
"{\n"
"  inherit (a) x y;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:717
msgid "inherit (a) x y;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:723
msgid "x = a.x; y = a.y;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:727
msgid "`inherit` also works inside `let` expressions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:731
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  inherit ({ x = 1; y = 2; }) x y;\n"
"in [ x y ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:738
msgid "[ 1 2 ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:745
msgid ""
"While this example is contrived, in more complex code you will regularly see "
"nested `let` expressions that re-use names from their outer scope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:747
msgid ""
"Here we use the attribute set `{ x = 1; y = 2; }` to have something non-"
"trivial to inherit from. The `let` expression inherits `x` and `y` from that "
"attribute set using `( )`, which is equivalent to writing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:750
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  x = { x = 1; y = 2; }.x;\n"
"  y = { x = 1; y = 2; }.y;\n"
"in"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:757
msgid ""
"The new inner scope now contains `x` and `y`, which are used in the list "
"`[ x y ]`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:762
msgid "String interpolation `${ ... }`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:764
msgid "Previously known as “antiquotation”."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:766
msgid ""
"The value of a Nix expression can be inserted into a character string with "
"the dollar-sign and braces (`${ }`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:770
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  name = \"Nix\";\n"
"in\n"
"\"hello ${name}\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:778
msgid "\"hello Nix\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:783
msgid ""
"Only character strings or values that can be represented as a character "
"string are allowed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:787
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  x = 1;\n"
"in\n"
"\"${x} + ${x} = ${x + x}\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:795
msgid ""
"error: cannot coerce an integer to a string\n"
"\n"
"       at «string»:4:2:\n"
"\n"
"            3| in\n"
"            4| \"${x} + ${x} = ${x + x}\"\n"
"             |  ^\n"
"            5|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:807
msgid "Interpolated expressions can be arbitrarily nested."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:809
msgid ""
"(This can become hard to read, and we recommend to avoid it in practice.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:813
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  a = \"no\";\n"
"in\n"
"\"${a + \" ${a + \" ${a}\"}\"}\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:821
msgid "\"no no no\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:827
msgid ""
"Any Nix expression where the value can be represented as a string can be "
"used within `${ }`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:829
msgid ""
"The `+` sign in the above expression is the [string concatenation operator]"
"(https://nix.dev/manual/nix/latest/language/operators#string-concatenation), "
"which takes two strings and produces a new string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:831
msgid ""
"The expression in the example is deliberately confusing in order to "
"demonstrate that arbitrarily nested string interpolations are possible, but "
"tend to be hard to read."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:833
msgid ""
"It denotes a string that contains the interpolation of concatenating the "
"value of `a` with a string that starts with a space and is followed by "
"another interpolated string. That second interpolated string is again the "
"result of concatenating the value of `a` and yet another string that starts "
"with a space and is followed by an interpolation of `a`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:837
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  a = \"one\";\n"
"  b = \"two\";\n"
"in\n"
"\"${a + b}\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:846
msgid "\"onetwo\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:851
msgid "Built-in functions are discussed in a [later section](libraries)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:855
msgid ""
"You may encounter strings that use the dollar sign (`$`) before an assigned "
"name, but no braces (`{ }`):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:857
msgid ""
"These are *not* interpolated strings, but usually denote variables in a "
"shell script."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:859
msgid ""
"In such cases, the use of names from the surrounding Nix expression is a "
"coincidence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:863
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  out = \"Nix\";\n"
"in\n"
"\"echo ${out} > $out\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:871
msgid "\"echo Nix > $out\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:877
msgid "<!-- TODO: link to escaping rules -->\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:880
msgid "Indented strings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:882
msgid "Also known as “multi-line strings”."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:884
msgid ""
"The Nix language offers convenience syntax for character strings which span "
"multiple lines that have common indentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:886
msgid "Indented strings are denoted by *double single quotes* (`'' ''`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:890
msgid ""
"''\n"
"multi\n"
"line\n"
"string\n"
"''"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:899
msgid "\"multi\\nline\\nstring\\n\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:904
msgid "Equal amounts of prepended white space are trimmed from the result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:908
msgid ""
"''\n"
"  one\n"
"   two\n"
"    three\n"
"''"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:917
msgid "\"one\\n two\\n  three\\n\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:923
msgid ""
"Indented strings also support [string interpolation](string-interpolation). "
"For details check the [documentation on string literals in the Nix language]"
"(https://nix.dev/manual/nix/2.24/language/syntax#string-literal)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:928
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1785
msgid "File system paths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:930
msgid "The Nix language offers convenience syntax for file system paths."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:932
msgid "Absolute paths always start with a slash (`/`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:936
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:941
msgid "/absolute/path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:946
msgid ""
"Paths are relative when they contain at least one slash (`/`) but do not "
"start with one. They evaluate to the path relative to the file containing "
"the expression."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:949
msgid ""
"The following examples assume the containing Nix file is in `/current/"
"directory` (or `nix repl` is run in `/current/directory`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:954
msgid "./relative"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:959
msgid "/current/directory/relative"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:966
msgid "relative/path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:971
msgid "/current/directory/relative/path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:976
msgid "One dot (`.`) denotes the current directory within the given path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:978
msgid ""
"You will often see the following expression, which specifies a Nix file's "
"directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:982
msgid "./."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:987
msgid "/current/directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:994
msgid ""
"Since relative paths must contain a slash (`/`) but must not start with one, "
"and the dot (`.`) denotes no change of directory, the combination `./.` "
"specifies the current directory as a relative path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:998
msgid "Two dots (`..`) denote the parent directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1002
msgid "../."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1007
msgid "/current"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1012
msgid ""
"Paths can be used in interpolated expressions – an [impure operation]"
"(impurities) we will cover in detail in a [later section](path-impurities)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1016
msgid "Lookup paths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1018
msgid "Also known as “angle bracket syntax”."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1022
msgid "<nixpkgs>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1027
msgid "/nix/var/nix/profiles/per-user/root/channels/nixpkgs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1032
msgid ""
"The value of a [lookup path](https://nix.dev/manual/nix/2.22/language/"
"constructs/lookup-path) is a file system path that depends on the value of "
"[`builtins.nixPath`](https://nix.dev/manual/nix/2.22/language/builtin-"
"constants#builtins-nixPath)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1034
msgid ""
"In practice, `<nixpkgs>` points to the file system path of some revision of "
"{term}`Nixpkgs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1036
msgid ""
"For example, `<nixpkgs/lib>` points to the subdirectory `lib` of that file "
"system path:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1038
msgid "<nixpkgs/lib>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1043
msgid "/nix/var/nix/profiles/per-user/root/channels/nixpkgs/lib"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1048
msgid ""
"While you will encounter many such examples, we recommend to [avoid lookup "
"paths](search-path) in production code, as they are [impurities](impurities) "
"which are not reproducible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1055
msgid "Functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1057
msgid ""
"Functions are everywhere in the Nix language and deserve particular "
"attention."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1059
msgid ""
"A function always takes exactly one argument. Argument and function body are "
"separated by a colon (`:`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1062
msgid "Wherever you find a colon (`:`) in Nix language code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1063
msgid "On its left is the function argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1064
msgid "On its right is the function body."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1066
msgid ""
"Function arguments are the third way, apart from [attribute sets](attrset) "
"and [`let` expressions](let), to assign names to values. Notably, values are "
"not known in advance: the names are placeholders that are filled when "
"[calling a function](calling-functions)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1069
msgid ""
"Function declarations in the Nix language can appear in different forms. "
"Each of them is explained in the following, and here is an overview:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1072
msgid "Single argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1074
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1121
msgid "x: x + 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1078
msgid "Multiple arguments via nesting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1080
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1274
msgid "x: y: x + y"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1084
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1330
msgid "Attribute set argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1086
msgid "{ a, b }: a + b"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1090
msgid "With default attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1092
msgid "{ a, b ? 0 }: a + b"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1096
msgid "With additional attributes allowed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1098
msgid "{ a, b, ...}: a + b"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1102
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1457
msgid "Named attribute set argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1104
msgid "args@{ a, b, ... }: a + b + args.c"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1108
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1477
msgid "or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1110
msgid "{ a, b, ... }@args: a + b + args.c"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1114
msgid ""
"Functions in the Nix language have no names. We say they are anonymous, and "
"call such a function a *lambda*.[^lambda]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1126
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1144
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1279
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1291
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1308
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1345
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1472
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1484
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1714
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1740
msgid "<LAMBDA>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1131
msgid "The `<LAMBDA>` indicates the resulting value is an anonymous function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1133
msgid "As with any other value, functions can be assigned to a name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1137
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = x: x + 1;\n"
"in f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1150
msgid "Calling functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1152
msgid "Also known as \"function application\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1154
msgid ""
"Calling a function with an argument means writing the argument after the "
"function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1158
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = x: x + 1;\n"
"in f 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1172
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = x: x.a;\n"
"in\n"
"f { a = 1; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1185
msgid ""
"The above example calls `f` on a literal attribute set. One can also pass "
"arguments by name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1190
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = x: x.a;\n"
"  v = { a = 1; };\n"
"in\n"
"f v"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1204
msgid ""
"Since function and argument are separated by white space, sometimes "
"parentheses (`( )`) are required to achieve the desired result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1208
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1623
msgid "(x: x + 1) 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1220
msgid ""
"This expression applies an anonymous function `x: x + 1` to the argument "
"`1`. The function has to be written in parentheses to distinguish it from "
"the argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1227
msgid ""
"List elements are also separated by white space, therefore the following are "
"different:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1229
msgid ""
"let\n"
" f = x: x + 1;\n"
" a = 1;\n"
"in [ (f a) ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1237
msgid "[ 2 ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1242
msgid ""
"let\n"
" f = x: x + 1;\n"
" a = 1;\n"
"in [ f a ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1250
msgid "[ <LAMBDA> 1 ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1255
msgid ""
"The first example reads: apply `f` to `a`, and put the result in a list. The "
"resulting list has one element."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1258
msgid ""
"The second example reads: put `f` and `a` in a list. The resulting list has "
"two elements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1261
msgid "Multiple arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1263
msgid "Also known as “[curried] functions”."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1265
msgid ""
"Nix functions take exactly one argument. Multiple arguments can be handled "
"by nesting functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1268
msgid ""
"Such a nested function can be used like a function that takes multiple "
"arguments, but offers additional flexibility."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1284
msgid "The above function is equivalent to"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1286
msgid "x: (y: x + y)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1296
msgid ""
"This function takes one argument and returns another function `y: x + y` "
"with `x` set to the value of that argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1300
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = x: y: x + y;\n"
"in\n"
"f 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1313
msgid ""
"Applying the function which results from `f 1` to another argument yields "
"the inner body `x + y` (with `x` set to `1` and `y` set to the other "
"argument), which can now be fully evaluated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1315
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = x: y: x + y;\n"
"in\n"
"f 1 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1328
msgid ""
"<!-- TODO: exercise - assign the lambda a name and do something with it -->\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1332
msgid "Also known as “keyword arguments” or “destructuring”."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1334
msgid ""
"Nix functions can be declared to require an attribute set with specific "
"structure as argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1336
msgid ""
"This is denoted by listing the expected attribute names separated by commas "
"(`,`) and enclosed in braces (`{ }`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1340
msgid "{a, b}: a + b"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1350
msgid ""
"The argument defines the exact attributes that have to be in that set. "
"Leaving out or passing additional attributes is an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1355
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = {a, b}: a + b;\n"
"in\n"
"f { a = 1; b = 2; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1370
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = {a, b}: a + b;\n"
"in\n"
"f { a = 1; b = 2; c = 3; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1378
msgid ""
"error: 'f' at (string):2:7 called with unexpected argument 'c'\n"
"\n"
"       at «string»:4:1:\n"
"\n"
"            3| in\n"
"            4| f { a = 1; b = 2; c = 3; }\n"
"             | ^\n"
"            5|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1390
msgid "<!-- TODO: not the same as x: x.a + x.b (!!!!) -->\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1392
msgid "Default values"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1394
msgid "Also known as “default arguments”."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1396
msgid "Destructured arguments can have default values for attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1398
msgid ""
"This is denoted by separating the attribute name and its default value with "
"a question mark (`?`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1400
msgid ""
"Attributes in the argument are not required if they have a default value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1404
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = {a, b ? 0}: a + b;\n"
"in\n"
"f { a = 1; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1419
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = {a ? 0, b ? 0}: a + b;\n"
"in\n"
"f { } # empty attribute set"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1427
msgid "0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1432
msgid "Additional attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1434
msgid "Additional attributes are allowed with an ellipsis (`...`):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1436
msgid "{a, b, ...}: a + b"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1440
msgid ""
"Unlike in the previous counter-example, passing an argument that contains "
"additional attributes is not an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1444
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = {a, b, ...}: a + b;\n"
"in\n"
"f { a = 1; b = 2; c = 3; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1459
msgid "Also known as “@ pattern”, “@ syntax”, or “‘at’ syntax”."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1461
msgid ""
"An attribute set argument can be given a name to be accessible as a whole."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1463
msgid ""
"This is denoted by prepending or appending the name to the attribute set "
"argument, separated by the at sign (`@`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1467
msgid "{a, b, ...}@args: a + b + args.c"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1479
msgid "args@{a, b, ...}: a + b + args.c"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1491
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  f = {a, b, ...}@args: a + b + args.c;\n"
"in\n"
"f { a = 1; b = 2; c = 3; }"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1499
msgid "6"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1505
msgid "Function libraries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1507
msgid ""
"In addition to the [built-in operators][operators] (`+`, `==`, `&&`, etc.), "
"there are two widely used libraries that *together* can be considered "
"standard for the Nix language. You need to know about both to understand and "
"navigate Nix language code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1510
msgid "<!-- TODO: find a place for operators -->\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1512
msgid ""
"We recommend to at least skim them to familiarise yourself with what is "
"available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1517
msgid "`builtins`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1519
msgid "Also known as “primitive operations” or “primops”."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1521
msgid ""
"Nix comes with many functions that are built into the language. They are "
"implemented in C++ as part of the Nix language interpreter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1525
msgid ""
"The Nix manual lists all [Built-in Functions][nix-builtins], and shows how "
"to use them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1528
msgid "These functions are available under the `builtins` constant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1532
msgid "builtins.toString"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1537
msgid "<PRIMOP>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1546
msgid "`import`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1548
msgid ""
"Most built-in functions are only accessible through `builtins`. A notable "
"exception is `import`, which is also available at the top level."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1551
msgid ""
"`import` takes a path to a Nix file, reads it to evaluate the contained Nix "
"expression, and returns the resulting value. If the path points to a "
"directory, the file `default.nix` in that directory is used instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1556
msgid "$ echo 1 + 2 > file.nix\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1560
msgid "import ./file.nix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1572
msgid ""
"The preceding shell command writes the contents `1 + 2` to the file `file."
"nix` in the current directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1574
msgid ""
"The above Nix expression refers to this file as `./file.nix`. `import` reads "
"the file and evaluates to the contained Nix expression."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1577
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1619
msgid "It is an error if the file system path does not exist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1579
msgid ""
"After reading `file.nix` the Nix expression is equivalent to the file "
"contents:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1592
msgid ""
"Since a Nix file can contain any Nix expression, `import`ed functions can be "
"applied to arguments immediately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1594
msgid ""
"That is, whenever you find additional tokens after a call to `import`, the "
"value it returns should be a function, and anything that follows are "
"arguments to that function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1598
msgid "$ echo \"x: x + 1\" > file.nix\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1602
msgid "import ./file.nix 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1614
msgid ""
"The preceding shell command writes the contents `x: x + 1` to the file `file."
"nix` in the current directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1616
msgid ""
"The above Nix expression refers to this file as `./file.nix`. `import ./file."
"nix` reads the file and evaluates to the contained Nix expression."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1621
msgid ""
"After reading the file, the Nix expression `import ./file.nix` is equivalent "
"to the file contents:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1633
msgid ""
"This applies the function `x: x + 1` to the argument `1`, and therefore "
"evaluates to `2`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1636
msgid ""
"Parentheses are required to separate function declaration from function "
"application."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1642
msgid "`pkgs.lib`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1644
msgid ""
"The [`nixpkgs`][nixpkgs] repository contains an attribute set called [`lib`]"
"[nixpkgs-lib], which provides a large number of useful functions. They are "
"implemented in the Nix language, as opposed to [`builtins`](builtins), which "
"are part of the language itself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1648
msgid ""
"The Nixpkgs manual lists all [Nixpkgs library functions][nixpkgs-functions]."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1654
msgid ""
"These functions are usually accessed through `pkgs.lib`, as the Nixpkgs "
"attribute set is given the name `pkgs` by convention."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1658
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  pkgs = import <nixpkgs> {};\n"
"in\n"
"pkgs.lib.strings.toUpper \"lookup paths considered harmful\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1666
msgid "LOOKUP PATHS CONSIDERED HARMFUL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1673
msgid ""
"This is a more complex example, but by now you should be familiar with all "
"its components."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1675
msgid ""
"The name `pkgs` is declared to be the expression `import`ed from some file. "
"That file's path is determined by the value of the lookup path `<nixpkgs>`, "
"which in turn is determined by the `$NIX_PATH` environment variable at the "
"time this expression is evaluated. As this expression happens to be a "
"function, it requires an argument to evaluate, and in this case passing an "
"empty attribute set `{}` is sufficient."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1679
msgid ""
"Now that `pkgs` is in scope of `let ... in ...`, its attributes can be "
"accessed. From the Nixpkgs manual one can determine that there exists a "
"function under [`lib.strings.toUpper`]."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1684
msgid ""
"For brevity, this example uses a lookup path to obtain *some version* of "
"Nixpkgs. The function `toUpper` is trivial enough that we can expect it not "
"to produce different results for different versions of Nixpkgs. Yet, more "
"sophisticated software is likely to suffer from such problems. A fully "
"reproducible example would therefore look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1689
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/"
"archive/06278c77b5d162e62df170fec307e83f1812d94b.tar.gz\";\n"
"  pkgs = import nixpkgs {};\n"
"in\n"
"pkgs.lib.strings.toUpper \"always pin your sources\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1698
msgid "ALWAYS PIN YOUR SOURCES"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1703
msgid "See [](pinning-nixpkgs) for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1705
msgid ""
"What you will also often see is that `pkgs` is passed as an argument to a "
"function. By convention one can assume that it refers to the Nixpkgs "
"attribute set, which has a `lib` attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1708
msgid ""
"{ pkgs, ... }:\n"
"pkgs.lib.strings.removePrefix \"no \" \"no true scotsman\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1719
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1745
msgid ""
"To make this function produce a result, you can write it to a file (e.g. "
"`file.nix`) and pass it an argument through `nix-instantiate`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1721
msgid ""
"$ nix-instantiate --eval file.nix --arg pkgs 'import <nixpkgs> {}'\n"
"\"true scotsman\"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1726
msgid ""
"Oftentimes you will see in NixOS configurations, and also within Nixpkgs, "
"that `lib` is passed directly. In that case one can assume that this `lib` "
"is equivalent to `pkgs.lib` where only `pkgs` is available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1731
msgid ""
"{ lib, ... }:\n"
"let\n"
"  to-be = true;\n"
"in\n"
"lib.trivial.or to-be (! to-be)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1747
msgid ""
"$ nix-instantiate --eval file.nix --arg lib '(import <nixpkgs> {}).lib'\n"
"true\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1752
msgid ""
"Sometimes both `pkgs` and `lib` are passed as arguments. In that case, one "
"can assume `pkgs.lib` and `lib` to be equivalent. This is done to improve "
"readability by avoiding repeated use of `pkgs.lib`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1758
msgid ""
"{ pkgs, lib, ... }:\n"
"# ... multiple uses of `pkgs`\n"
"# ... multiple uses of `lib`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1766
msgid ""
"For historical reasons, some of the functions in `pkgs.lib` are equivalent "
"to [`builtins`](builtins) of the same name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1769
msgid "Impurities"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1771
msgid ""
"So far we have only covered what we call *pure expressions*: declaring data "
"and transforming it with functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1774
msgid ""
"In practice, describing derivations – the Nix language's defining feature, "
"which enables functional programming with the file system – requires "
"observing the outside world. We will discuss [derivations](derivations) "
"later in the tutorial."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1777
msgid ""
"There is only one impurity in the Nix language that is relevant here: "
"reading files from the file system as *build inputs*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1780
msgid ""
"Build inputs are files that derivations refer to in order to describe how to "
"derive new files. When run, a derivation will only have access to explicitly "
"declared build inputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1783
msgid ""
"The only way to specify build inputs in the Nix language is explicitly with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1786
msgid "Dedicated functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1788
msgid ""
"Nix and the Nix language refer to files by their content hash. If file "
"contents are not known in advance, it's unavoidable to read files during "
"expression evaluation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1791
msgid ""
"Nix supports other types of impure expressions, such as [lookup paths]"
"(search-path) or the constant [`builtins.currentSystem`](https://nix.dev/"
"manual/nix/stable/language/builtin-constants.html#builtins-currentSystem). "
"We do not cover those here in more detail, as they do not matter for how the "
"Nix language works in principle, and because they are discouraged for the "
"very reason of breaking reproducibility."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1796
msgid "Paths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1798
msgid ""
"Whenever a file system path is used in [string interpolation](string-"
"interpolation), the contents of that file are copied to a special location "
"in the file system, the *Nix store*, as a side effect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1800
msgid ""
"The evaluated string then contains the Nix store path assigned to that file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1802
msgid "<!-- TODO: link to explanation of the Nix store -->\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1806
msgid "$ echo 123 > data\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1810
msgid "\"${./data}\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1815
msgid "\"/nix/store/h1qj5h5n05b5dl5q4nldrqq8mdg7dhqk-data\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1822
msgid ""
"The preceding shell command writes the characters `123` to the file `data` "
"in the current directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1824
msgid ""
"The above Nix expression refers to this file as `./data` and converts the "
"file system path to an [interpolated string](string-interpolation) `${ ... }"
"`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1826
msgid ""
"Such interpolated expressions must evaluate to something that can be "
"represented as a character string. A file system path is such a value, and "
"its character string representation is the corresponding Nix store path:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1829
msgid "/nix/store/<hash>-<name>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1833
msgid ""
"The Nix store path is obtained by taking the hash of the file's contents "
"(`<hash>`) and combining it with the file name (`<name>`). The file is "
"copied into the Nix store directory `/nix/store` as a side effect of "
"evaluation. It is an error if the file system path does not exist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1839
msgid ""
"For directories the same thing happens: The entire directory (including "
"nested files and directories) is copied to the Nix store, and the evaluated "
"string becomes the Nix store path of the directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1841
msgid "Fetchers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1843
msgid ""
"Files to be used as build inputs do not have to come from the file system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1845
msgid ""
"The Nix language provides built-in impure functions to fetch files over the "
"network during evaluation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1847
msgid ""
"[`builtins.fetchurl`](https://nix.dev/manual/nix/stable/language/builtins."
"html#builtins-fetchurl)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1848
msgid ""
"[`builtins.fetchTarball`](https://nix.dev/manual/nix/stable/language/"
"builtins.html#builtins-fetchTarball)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1849
msgid ""
"[`builtins.fetchGit`](https://nix.dev/manual/nix/stable/language/builtins."
"html#builtins-fetchGit)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1850
msgid ""
"[`builtins.fetchClosure`](https://nix.dev/manual/nix/stable/language/"
"builtins.html#builtins-fetchClosure)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1852
msgid "These functions evaluate to a file system path in the Nix store."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1856
msgid ""
"builtins.fetchurl \"https://github.com/NixOS/nix/"
"archive/7c3ab5751568a0bc63430b33a5169c5e4784a0ff.tar.gz\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1861
msgid ""
"\"/nix/"
"store/7dhgs330clj36384akg86140fqkgh8zf-7c3ab5751568a0bc63430b33a5169c5e4784a0ff."
"tar.gz\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1866
msgid ""
"Some of them add extra convenience, such as automatically unpacking archives."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1870
msgid ""
"builtins.fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nix/"
"archive/7c3ab5751568a0bc63430b33a5169c5e4784a0ff.tar.gz\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1875
msgid "\"/nix/store/d59llm96vgis5fy231x6m7nrijs0ww36-source\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1881
msgid ""
"The Nixpkgs manual on [Fetchers][nixpkgs-fetchers] lists numerous additional "
"library functions to fetch files over the network."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1884
msgid "It is an error if the network request fails."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1889
msgid "Derivations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1892
msgid "Derivations are at the core of both Nix and the Nix language:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1893
msgid "The Nix language is used to describe derivations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1894
msgid "Nix runs derivations to produce *build results*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1895
msgid "Build results can in turn be used as inputs for other derivations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1897
msgid ""
"The Nix language primitive to declare a derivation is the built-in impure "
"function `derivation`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1899
msgid ""
"It is usually wrapped by the Nixpkgs build mechanism `stdenv.mkDerivation`, "
"which hides much of the complexity involved in non-trivial build procedures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1902
msgid "You will probably never encounter `derivation` in practice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1905
msgid ""
"Whenever you encounter `mkDerivation`, it denotes something that Nix will "
"eventually *build*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1907
msgid "Example: [a package using `mkDerivation`](mkDerivation-example)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1909
msgid ""
"The evaluation result of `derivation` (and `mkDerivation`) is an [attribute "
"set](attrset) with a certain structure and a special property: It can be "
"used in [string interpolation](string-interpolation), and in that case "
"evaluates to the Nix store path of its build result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1914
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  pkgs = import <nixpkgs> {};\n"
"in \"${pkgs.nix}\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1921
msgid "\"/nix/store/sv2srrjddrp2isghmrla8s6lazbzmikd-nix-2.11.0\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1927
msgid ""
"Your output may differ. It may produce a different hash or even a different "
"package version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1930
msgid ""
"A derivation's output path is fully determined by its inputs, which in this "
"case come from *some* version of Nixpkgs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1932
msgid ""
"This is why we recommend to [avoid lookup paths](search-path) to ensure "
"predictable outcomes, except in examples intended for illustration only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1937
msgid ""
"The example imports the Nix expression from the lookup path `<nixpkgs>`, and "
"applies the resulting function to an empty attribute set `{}`. Its output is "
"assigned the name `pkgs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1940
msgid ""
"Converting the attribute `pkgs.nix` to a string with [string interpolation]"
"(string-interpolation) is allowed, as `pkgs.nix` is a derivation. That is, "
"ultimately `pkgs.nix` boils down to a call to `derivation`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1943
msgid ""
"The resulting string is the file system path where the build result of that "
"derivation will end up."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1945
msgid ""
"There is more depth to the inner workings of derivations, but at this point "
"it should be enough to know that such expressions evaluate to Nix store "
"paths."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1949
msgid ""
"String interpolation on derivations is used to refer to their build results "
"as file system paths when declaring new derivations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1951
msgid ""
"This allows constructing arbitrarily complex compositions of derivations "
"with the Nix language."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1953
msgid "Worked examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1955
msgid ""
"So far we have seen artificial examples illustrating the various constructs "
"in the Nix language."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1957
msgid ""
"You should now be able to read Nix language code for simple packages and "
"configurations, and come up with similar explanations of the following "
"practical examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1960
msgid ""
"The goal of the following exercises is not to understand what the code means "
"or how it works, but how it is structured in terms of functions, attribute "
"sets, and other Nix language data types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1963
msgid "Shell environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1965
msgid ""
"{ pkgs ? import <nixpkgs> {} }:\n"
"let\n"
"  message = \"hello world\";\n"
"in\n"
"pkgs.mkShellNoCC {\n"
"  packages = with pkgs; [ cowsay ];\n"
"  shellHook = ''\n"
"    cowsay ${message}\n"
"  '';\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1978
msgid ""
"This example declares a shell environment (which runs the `shellHook` on "
"initialization)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1980
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2008
#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2048
msgid "Explanation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1982
msgid ""
"This expression is a function that takes an attribute set as its argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1983
msgid ""
"If the argument has the attribute `pkgs`, it will be used in the function "
"body. Otherwise, by default, import the Nix expression in the file found on "
"the lookup path `<nixpkgs>` (which is a function in this case), call the "
"function with an empty attribute set, and use the resulting value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1985
msgid "The name `message` is bound to the string value `\"hello world\"`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1986
msgid ""
"The attribute `mkShellNoCC` of the `pkgs` set is a function that is passed "
"an attribute set as argument. Its return value is also the result of the "
"outer function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1988
msgid ""
"The attribute set passed to `mkShellNoCC` has the attributes `packages` (set "
"to a list with one element: the `cowsay` attribute from `pkgs`) and "
"`shellHook` (set to an indented string)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1989
msgid ""
"The indented string contains an interpolated expression, which will expand "
"the value of `message` to yield `\"hello world\"`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1992
msgid "NixOS configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:1994
msgid ""
"{ config, pkgs, ... }: {\n"
"\n"
"  imports = [ ./hardware-configuration.nix ];\n"
"\n"
"  environment.systemPackages = with pkgs; [ git ];\n"
"\n"
"  # ...\n"
"\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2006
msgid "This example is (part of) a NixOS configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2010
msgid ""
"This expression is a function that takes an attribute set as an argument. It "
"returns an attribute set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2012
msgid ""
"The argument must at least have the attributes `config` and `pkgs`, and may "
"have more attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2013
msgid ""
"The returned attribute set contains the attributes `imports` and "
"`environment`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2014
msgid ""
"`imports` is a list with one element: a path to a file next to this Nix "
"file, called `hardware-configuration.nix`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2017
msgid ""
"`imports` is not the impure built-in `import`, but a regular attribute name!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2019
msgid ""
"`environment` is itself an attribute set with one attribute "
"`systemPackages`, which will evaluate to a list with one element: the `git` "
"attribute from the `pkgs` set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2020
msgid "The `config` argument is not (shown to be) used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2023
msgid "Package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2025
msgid ""
"{ lib, stdenv, fetchurl }:\n"
"\n"
"stdenv.mkDerivation rec {\n"
"\n"
"  pname = \"hello\";\n"
"\n"
"  version = \"2.12\";\n"
"\n"
"  src = fetchurl {\n"
"    url = \"mirror://gnu/${pname}/${pname}-${version}.tar.gz\";\n"
"    sha256 = \"1ayhp9v4m4rdhjmnl2bq3cibrbqqkgjbl3s7yk2nhlh8vj3ay16g\";\n"
"  };\n"
"\n"
"  meta = with lib; {\n"
"    license = licenses.gpl3Plus;\n"
"  };\n"
"\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2046
msgid "This example is a (simplified) package declaration from Nixpkgs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2050
msgid ""
"This expression is a function that takes an attribute set which must have "
"exactly the attributes `lib`, `stdenv`, and `fetchurl`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2051
msgid ""
"It returns the result of evaluating the function `mkDerivation`, which is an "
"attribute of `stdenv`, applied to a recursive set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2052
msgid ""
"The recursive set passed to `mkDerivation` uses its own `pname` and "
"`version` attributes in the argument to the function `fetchurl`. `fetchurl` "
"itself comes from the outer function's arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2054
msgid ""
"The `meta` attribute is itself an attribute set, where the `license` "
"attribute has the value that was assigned to the nested attribute `lib."
"licenses.gpl3Plus`."
msgstr ""

