msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2092
msgid "{ x, y, z }: (x y) z.a"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2096
msgid "How do we know..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2097
msgid ""
"that `x` will be a function that, given an argument, returns a function?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2098
msgid ""
"that, given `x` is a function, `y` will be an appropriate argument to `x`?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2099
msgid ""
"that, given `(x y)` is a function, `z.a` will be an appropriate argument to "
"`(x y)`?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2100
msgid "that `z` will be an attribute set at all?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2101
msgid "that, given `z` is an attribute set, it will have an attribute `a`?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2102
msgid "which data type `y` and `z.a` will be?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2103
msgid "the data type of the end result?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2105
msgid ""
"And how does the caller of this function know that it requires an attribute "
"set with attributes `x`, `y`, `z`?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nix-language.md:2107
msgid ""
